005package edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command;
006
007import edu.wpi.first.util.sendable.SendableBuilder;
008import java.util.Set;
009
010/**
011 * A class used internally to wrap commands while overriding a specific method; all other methods
012 * will call through to the wrapped command.
013 *
014 * <p>The rules for command compositions apply: command instances that are passed to it cannot be
015 * added to any other composition or scheduled individually, and the composition requires all
016 * subsystems its components require.
017 */
018public abstract class WrapperCommand extends Command {
019  /** Command being wrapped. */
020  protected final Command m_command;
021
022  /**
023   * Wrap a command.
024   *
025   * @param command the command being wrapped. Trying to directly schedule this command or add it to
026   *     a composition will throw an exception.
027   */
028  @SuppressWarnings("this-escape")
029  protected WrapperCommand(Command command) {
030    CommandScheduler.getInstance().registerComposedCommands(command);
031    m_command = command;
032    // copy the wrapped command's name
033    setName(command.getName());
034  }
035
036  /** The initial subroutine of a command. Called once when the command is initially scheduled. */
037  @Override
038  public void initialize() {
039    m_command.initialize();
040  }
041
042  /** The main body of a command. Called repeatedly while the command is scheduled. */
043  @Override
044  public void execute() {
045    m_command.execute();
046  }
047
048  /**
049   * The action to take when the command ends. Called when either the command finishes normally, or
050   * when it interrupted/canceled.
051   *
052   * <p>Do not schedule commands here that share requirements with this command. Use {@link
053   * #andThen(Command...)} instead.
054   *
055   * @param interrupted whether the command was interrupted/canceled
056   */
057  @Override
058  public void end(boolean interrupted) {
059    m_command.end(interrupted);
060  }
061
062  /**
063   * Whether the command has finished. Once a command finishes, the scheduler will call its end()
064   * method and un-schedule it.
065   *
066   * @return whether the command has finished.
067   */
068  @Override
069  public boolean isFinished() {
070    return m_command.isFinished();
071  }
072
073  /**
074   * Specifies the set of subsystems used by this command. Two commands cannot use the same
075   * subsystem at the same time. If the command is scheduled as interruptible and another command is
076   * scheduled that shares a requirement, the command will be interrupted. Else, the command will
077   * not be scheduled. If no subsystems are required, return an empty set.
078   *
079   * <p>Note: it is recommended that user implementations contain the requirements as a field, and
080   * return that field here, rather than allocating a new set every time this is called.
081   *
082   * @return the set of subsystems that are required
083   */
084  @Override
085  public Set<Subsystem> getRequirements() {
086    return m_command.getRequirements();
087  }
088
089  /**
090   * Whether the given command should run when the robot is disabled. Override to return true if the
091   * command should run when disabled.
092   *
093   * @return whether the command should run when the robot is disabled
094   */
095  @Override
096  public boolean runsWhenDisabled() {
097    return m_command.runsWhenDisabled();
098  }
099
100  @Override
101  public InterruptionBehavior getInterruptionBehavior() {
102    return m_command.getInterruptionBehavior();
103  }
104
105  @Override
106  public void initSendable(SendableBuilder builder) {
107    m_command.initSendable(builder);
108  }
109}
